		<br>
		<table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%">
		<tr><td>Greetings Milo,<P>

 I am one of the few people who is a female in real life as well as in
game. As many already know, most female characters are actually played by guys
 (and the reason varies depending on who you talk to).  However, it seems
to be that this game was designed solely for men with little consideration to the women.<P>

 You know what I'm talking about, I'm sure you've heard it before.  The inequity when it comes to characters without any armor. Female Barbarians, Wood Elves, Dark Elves and Half Elves start with such little clothing on that it would make some people blush.  Female Dark
Elves run about with their little blue asses hanging out of their leather
'chaps'. High Elves, in leather, look as though they should be hanging that
cleavage off of a street corner begging for a few spare copper for a 'date'.
Humans, Dark Elves, Wood Elves in chain?  What, are we shopping at the Victoria's Secret for chainmail?  Oh, and let's not forget about the wonderful thong that the Half Elves get.<P>

 Talk about sexist!  While the under-sexed over-excited male geeks of this generation sit before their computers staring at the screen with a little bit of drool dangling at the right corner of their mouths, what are us females left with?  On most character models the male characters, when unclothed, look clothed!  When clothed, they look like a normal, clothed individual would look!  The difference is startling, and needless to say more than a little bit sexist.<P>

 So now that you've heard my complaints about it, perhaps you can answer
two questions: What POSSIBLE explanation can you (or anyone out there at
Verant) give me for this GIANT inequity?  Secondly, are there ANY females working
at Verant in something other than Customer Service or Sales.<P>

 Stacy Griebel<P>


 <I>Hello Milo,<P>

 First off, please accept my compliments on an overall EXCELLENT job of modeling the characters for EQ. Your passion and commitment to your work
is apparent, and the entire player community is the beneficiary. Well done.<P>

 Some questions:<P>

 - I have noticed that ALL the player characters have the physiques of
Greek gods. All the women are busty, leggy and thin, all the men are broad-shouldered, lean and ready to walk the runway in front of Versace (granted Trolls, Ogres, Halflings, etc. are an exception, but you get the idea). Why did Verant make this decision? I would think that it would make the world more colorful and diverse to actually have characters who were fat, skinny, or just plain ugly. I understand and accept that EQ is a fantasy world, but I think that the best fantasy is extrapolated from reality, and is thus believable and transporting. I was curious if the decision to make EQ a world of only beautiful people was rooted in technical constraints? Love of beauty? What?<P>

 - Just a thought. While I do think overall, your work is fantastic, I was wondering about the default posture for most Humans/Barbarians/Elves. Most of them, when simply standing at rest, seem to have their butts/chests protruding at a pretty exaggerated angle, while their arms are bent with
the elbows back. It looks a little strange to me. I was wonder why this is?<P>

 - Do you only model monsters/PC's? Or do you also do some of the
landscapes, structures, when they need another hand?<P>

 Myke</I><P>

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>
   Yes, we do have quite a few women fulfilling various roles here at
Verant Interactive, all of whom are crucial to the ongoing success of
the company (including those in our customer service department).
Two of them, Sabrina Fox and Rosie Cosgrove, have been essential
members of the EverQuest team from day one.  Sabrina's duties have
included designing and modeling many of EQ's dungeons, and Rosie
is the game's lead artist.  It's been reported so many times that it
should be common knowledge in the EQ community, by now: more
than anyone else, it was Rosie (a woman) who pushed for player
characters with tight, hard bodies and healthy endowments.  She says
that she did that because, in a fantasy world, most people are going
to want to be Venuses and Adonises. That sounds reasonable to me.<P>

   As for Myke's other questions, I never made any animations, nor
did I ever create any environmental geometry (except for most of
Norrath's statues).<P>

