<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>
   I really don't know how much EQ makes every month, nor do I know
how much of that money is kept by Verant Interactive.  Speculating about
periodic profits can be entertaining, but the fact is that there are really
only
a handful of people at Verant and Sony who know the whole financial
picture, and I wouldn't be surprised to discover that your figure of nine
megs of gross earnings per month is way off, one way or the other.  In any
case, I'm sorry that you don't think that the game is worth ten bucks per
month.  I eat fairly moderately, and I often spend more than that on a
single day's worth of grub.  Other companies with games similar to ours
are charging just as much as we, even though their games are half as good,
at best.  If it had been up to me, I'd have charged you players *more*
than ten USD per month.  EverQuest is a steal, in my opinion.<P>

   In response to another of your questions, we originally had close to
thirty people on the EQ team; that amount has increased quite a bit,
thanks to maintenance and expansion requirements.  Note that the costs
associated with this increase of staff have not been passed on to our
customers.<P>

   And no, Sony most certainly do not *give* us money -- not without
expecting us to give it back to them with interest.<P>

